lines.pos: rb vb , rb in dt vbn nn vbz to jj nn .

lines.text: But errors are compromise formations. They mean some success and some

lines.text: One day the discovery was made that the disease symptoms of certain

lines.text: We will not, however, pursue this historical path, but enter upon the

lines.text: neuroses, but the dream itself is also a neurotic symptom, and in fact

lines.text: one which possesses for us the incalculable advantage of occurring in
lines.pos: cd wdt vbz in prp dt jj nn in vbg in

lines.pos: nn . dt nn in dt nn nn prp in nns wrb rb

lines.pos: nn nnp nnp cc jj nnp nnp

lines.text: We have not studied the problem of errors in vain. Thanks to our efforts

lines.text: THIRTEENTH LECTURE
lines.pos: jj nnp

lines.text: THE DREAM
lines.pos: dt nnp

lines.text: _Archaic Remnants and Infantilism in the Dream_
lines.pos: nn nnps cc nnp in dt nnp

lines.text: Let us revert to our conclusion that the dream-work, under the influence
lines.pos: vb prp vb to prp$ nn in dt nn , in dt nn

lines.text: of the dream censorship, transforms the latent dream thoughts into some
lines.pos: in dt nn nn , vbz dt jj nn nns in dt

lines.text: other form of expression. The latent thoughts are no other than the
lines.pos: jj nn in nn . dt jj nns vbp dt jj in dt

lines.text: conscious thoughts known to us in our waking hours; the new mode of
lines.pos: jj nns vbn to prp in prp$ vbg nns ; dt jj nn in

lines.text: expression is incomprehensible to us because of its many-sided features.
lines.pos: nn vbz jj to prp in in prp$ vbn nns .

lines.text: We have said it extends back to conditions of our intellectual
lines.pos: prp vbp vbd prp vbz rb to nns in prp$ jj

lines.text: development which we have long progressed beyond, to the language of
lines.pos: nn wdt prp vbp jj vbd in , to dt nn in

lines.text: pictures, the symbol-representations, perhaps to those conditions which
lines.pos: nns , dt nns , rb to dt nns wdt

lines.text: were in force before the development of our language of thought. So we
lines.pos: vbd in nn in dt nn in prp$ nn in vbd . rb prp

lines.text: called the mode of expression of the dream-work the archaic or
lines.pos: vbn dt nn in nn in dt nn dt jj cc

lines.text: regressive.
lines.pos: jj .

lines.text: You may conclude that as a result of the deeper study of the dream-work
lines.pos: prp md vb in in dt nn in dt jjr nn in dt nn

lines.text: we gain valuable information about the rather unknown beginnings of our
lines.pos: prp nn jj nn in dt jj jj nns in prp$

lines.text: intellectual development. I trust this will be true, but this work has
lines.pos: jj nn . nnp nn dt md vb jj , cc dt nn vbz

lines.text: not, up to the present time, been undertaken. The antiquity into which
lines.pos: rb , in to dt jj nn , vbn vbn . dt nn in wdt

lines.text: the dream-work carries us back is of a double aspect, firstly, the
lines.pos: dt nn vbz prp rb vbz in dt jj nn , rb , dt

lines.text: individual antiquity, childhood; and, secondly (in so far as every
lines.pos: jj nn , nn ; cc , rb ( in rb rb in dt

lines.text: individual in his childhood lives over again in some more or less
lines.pos: jj in prp$ nn vbz in rb in dt jjr cc jjr

lines.text: abbreviated manner the entire development of the human race), also this
lines.pos: jj nn dt jj nn in dt jj nn ) , rb dt

lines.text: antiquity, the philogenetic. That we shall be able to differentiate
lines.pos: nn , dt nn . in prp md vb jj to vb

lines.text: which part of the latent psychic proceeding has its source in the
lines.pos: wdt nn in dt jj jj vbg vbz prp$ nn in dt

lines.text: individual, and which part in the philogenetic antiquity is not
lines.pos: jj , cc wdt nn in dt nn nn vbz rb

lines.text: improbable. In this connection it appears to me, for example, that the
lines.pos: jj . in dt nn prp vbz to prp , in nn , in dt

lines.text: symbolic relations which the individual has never learned are ground for
lines.pos: jj nns wdt dt jj vbz rb vbd vbp nn in

lines.text: the belief that they should be regarded as a philogenetic inheritance.
lines.pos: dt nn in prp md vb vbn in dt nn nn .

lines.text: However, this is not the only archaic characteristic of the dream. You
lines.pos: rb , dt nns rb dt rb jj jj in dt nn . prp

lines.text: probably all know from your own experiences the peculiar amnesia, that
lines.pos: rb dt nn in prp$ jj nns dt jj nn , in

lines.text: is, loss of memory, concerning childhood. I mean the fact that the first
lines.pos: vbz , nn in nn , vbg nn . nnp vb dt nn in dt nn

lines.text: years, to the fifth, sixth or eighth, have not left the same traces in
lines.pos: nns , to dt jj , jj cc jj , vbp rb vbn dt jj nns in

lines.text: our memory as have later experiences. One meets with individual persons,
lines.pos: prp$ nn in vbp rb nns . cd vbz in jj nns ,

lines.text: to be sure, who can boast of a continuous memory from the very beginning
lines.pos: to vb jj , wp md vbp in dt jj nn in dt jj vbg

lines.text: to the present day, but the other condition, that of a gap in the
lines.pos: to dt jj nn , cc dt jj nn , in in dt nn in dt

lines.text: memory, is far more frequent. I believe we have not laid enough stress
lines.pos: nn , vbz rb jjr jj . nnp vbp prp vbp rb vbn rb nn

lines.text: on this fact. The child is able to speak well at the age of two, it soon
lines.pos: in dt nn . dt nn vbz jj to vb rb in dt nn in cd , prp rb

lines.text: shows that it can become adjusted to the most complicated psychic
lines.pos: vbz in prp md vb vbn to dt jj vbn jj

lines.text: situations, and makes remarks which years later are retold to it, but
lines.pos: nns , cc vbz nns wdt nns rb vbp nn to prp , cc

lines.text: which it has itself entirely forgotten. Besides, the memory in the early
lines.pos: wdt prp vbz prp rb vbn . in , dt nn in dt rb

lines.text: years is more facile, because it is less burdened than in later years.
lines.pos: nns vbz jjr jj , in prp vbz jjr vbn in in rb nns .

lines.text: Nor is there any reason for considering the memory-function as a
lines.pos: cc vbz ex dt nn in vbg dt nn in dt

lines.text: particularly high or difficult psychic performance; in fact, the
lines.pos: rb jj cc jj jj nn ; in nn , dt

lines.text: contrary is true, and you can find a good memory in persons who stand
lines.pos: jj vbz jj , cc prp md vb dt jj nn in nns wp vb

lines.text: very low intellectually.
lines.pos: rb jj rb .

lines.text: As a second peculiarity closely related to the first, I must point out
lines.pos: in dt nn nn rb vbn to dt nn , nnp md nn in

lines.text: that certain well-preserved memories, for the most part formatively
lines.pos: in jj vbn nns , in dt jj nn rb

lines.text: experienced, stand forth in this memory-void which surrounds the first
lines.pos: vbn , vb rb in dt nn wdt vbz dt nn

lines.text: years of childhood and do not justify this hypothesis. Our memory deals
lines.pos: nns in nn cc vbp rb vb dt nns . prp$ nn vbz

lines.text: selectively with its later materials, with impressions which come to us
lines.pos: rb in prp$ rb nns , in nns wdt vb to prp

lines.text: in later life. It retains the important and discards the unimportant.
lines.pos: in rb nn . prp vbz dt jj cc nns dt jj .

lines.text: This is not true of the retained childhood memories. They do not bespeak
lines.pos: dt nns rb jj in dt vbn nn nns . prp vbp rb vbp

lines.text: necessarily important experiences of childhood, not even such as from
lines.pos: rb jj nns in nn , rb rb jj in in

lines.text: the viewpoint of the child need appear of importance. They are often so
lines.pos: dt nn in dt nn vbn vb in nn . prp vbp rb rb

lines.text: banal and intrinsically so meaningless that we ask ourselves in wonder
lines.pos: jj cc rb rb jj in prp vb prp in nn

lines.text: why just these details have escaped being forgotten. I once endeavored
lines.pos: wrb rb dt nns vbp vbd vbg vbn . nnp rb vbd

lines.text: to approach the riddle of childhood amnesia and the interrupted memory
lines.pos: to nn dt nn in nn nn cc dt vbn nn

lines.text: remnants with the help of analysis, and I arrived at the conclusion that
lines.pos: nns in dt nn in nns , cc nnp vbd in dt nn in

lines.text: in the case of the child, too, only the important has remained in the
lines.pos: in dt nn in dt nn , rb , rb dt jj vbz vbd in dt

lines.text: memory, except that by means of the process of condensation already
lines.pos: nn , in in in vbz in dt nn in nn rb

lines.text: known to you, and especially by means of distortion, the important is
lines.pos: vbn to prp , cc rb in vbz in nn , dt jj vbz

lines.text: represented in the memory by something that appears unimportant. For
lines.pos: vbn in dt nn in nn in vbz jj . in

lines.text: this reason I have called these childhood memories "disguise-memories,"
lines.pos: dt nn nnp vbp vbn dt nn nns " nns , "

lines.text: memories used to conceal; by means of careful analysis one is able to
lines.pos: nns vbn to vb ; in vbz in jj nns cd vbz jj to

lines.text: develop out of them everything that is forgotten.
lines.pos: vb in in prp nn in vbz vbn .

lines.text: In psychoanalytic treatment we are regularly called upon to fill out the
lines.pos: in jj nn prp vbp rb vbn in to vb in dt

lines.text: infantile memory gaps, and in so far as the cure is to any degree
lines.pos: jj nn nns , cc in rb rb in dt nn vbz to dt nn

lines.text: successful, we are able again to bring to light the content of the
lines.pos: jj , prp vbp jj rb to vb to nn dt nn in dt

lines.text: childhood years thus clouded in forgetfulness. These impressions have
lines.pos: nn nns rb vbn in nn . dt nns vbp

lines.text: never really been forgotten, they have only been inaccessible, latent,
lines.pos: rb rb vbn vbn , prp vbp rb vbn jj , jj ,

lines.text: have belonged to the unconscious. But sometimes they bob up out of the
lines.pos: vbp vbd to dt jj . cc rb prp nn in in in dt

lines.text: unconscious spontaneously, and, as a matter of fact, this is what
lines.pos: jj rb , cc , in dt nn in nn , dt nns wp

lines.text: happens in dreams. It is apparent that the dream life knows how to find
lines.pos: vbz in nns . prp vbz jj in dt nn nn vbz wrb to vb

lines.text: the entrance to these latent, infantile experiences. Beautiful examples
lines.pos: dt nn to dt jj , jj nns . jj nns

lines.text: of this occur in literature, and I myself can present such an example. I
lines.pos: in dt nn in nn , cc nnp prp md jj jj dt nn . nnp

lines.text: once dreamed in a certain connection of a person who must have performed
lines.pos: rb vbd in dt jj nn in dt nn wp md vbp vbn

lines.text: some service for me, and whom I clearly saw. He was a one-eyed man,
lines.pos: dt nn in prp , cc wp nnp rb vbd . prp vbd dt vbn nn ,

lines.text: short in stature, stout, his head deeply sunk into his neck. I concluded
lines.pos: jj in nn , jj , prp$ nn rb vbn in prp$ nn . nnp vbd

lines.text: from the content that he was a physician. Luckily I was able to ask my
lines.pos: in dt nn in prp vbd dt nn . rb nnp vbd jj to vb prp$

lines.text: mother, who was still living, how the physician in my birth-place, which
lines.pos: nn , wp vbd rb vbg , wrb dt nn in prp$ nn , wdt

lines.text: I left when I was three years old, looked, and I learned from her that
lines.pos: nnp vbn wrb nnp vbd cd nns jj , vbd , cc nnp vbd in prp$ in

lines.text: he had one eye, was short and stout, with his head sunk into his neck,
lines.pos: prp vbd cd nn , vbd jj cc jj , in prp$ nn vbn in prp$ nn ,

lines.text: and also learned at what forgotten mishap he had been of service to me.
lines.pos: cc rb vbd in wp vbn nn prp vbd vbn in nn to prp .

lines.text: This control over the forgotten material of childhood years is, then, a
lines.pos: dt nn in dt nn jj in nn nns vbz , rb , dt

lines.text: further archaic tendency of the dream.
lines.pos: jj jj nn in dt nn .

lines.text: The same information may be made use of in another of the puzzles that
lines.pos: dt jj nn md vb vbn nn in in dt in dt nns in

lines.text: have presented themselves to us. You will recall how astonished people
lines.pos: vbp vbn prp to prp . prp md vb wrb vbn nns

lines.text: were when we came to the conclusion that the stimuli which gave rise to
lines.pos: vbd wrb prp vbd to dt nn in dt nns wdt vbd nn to

lines.text: dreams were extremely bad and licentious sexual desires which have made
lines.pos: nns vbd rb jj cc nns jj nns wdt vbp vbn

lines.text: dream-censorship and dream-distortion necessary. After we have
lines.pos: nn cc nn jj . in prp vbp

lines.text: interpreted such a dream for the dreamer and he, in the most favorable
lines.pos: vbn jj dt nn in dt nn cc prp , in dt jj jj

lines.text: circumstances does not attack the interpretation itself, he almost
lines.pos: nns vbz rb nn dt nn prp , prp rb

lines.text: always asks the question whence such a wish comes, since it seems

lines.text: The closest analogies to these conditions of our neurotics are furnished

lines.pos: nn , md dt jj vb vbn in jj vbz .

lines.text: This analogy tempts us to classify as traumatic those experiences as

lines.text: By thus bringing into prominence the unconscious in psychic life, we
lines.pos: in rb vbg in nn dt jj in jj nn , prp

lines.text: _Resistance and Suppression_
lines.pos: nn cc nnp

lines.text: In order to progress in our understanding of the neuroses, we need new
lines.pos: in nn to nn in prp$ vbg in dt nns , prp vbn jj

lines.text: experiences and we are about to obtain two. Both are very remarkable and
lines.pos: nns cc prp vbp in to vb cd . nnp vbp rb jj cc

lines.text: were at the time of their discovery, very surprising. You are, of
lines.pos: vbd in dt nn in prp$ nn , rb jj . prp vbp , in

lines.pos: nn , vbn in nn in prp$ nns in dt jj nn .

lines.text: In the first place: When we undertake to cure a patient, to free him
lines.pos: in dt nn nn : wrb prp vb to nn dt nn , to jj prp

lines.text: from the symptoms of his malady, he confronts us with a vigorous,

lines.text: tenacious resistance that lasts during the whole time of the treatment.
lines.pos: jj nn in vbz in dt jj nn in dt nn .

lines.pos: dt jjs nn vbz rb to vb dt nn to dt nns nns ,

lines.text: order to excuse the length or the failure of our treatment. The patient,
lines.pos: nn to nn dt nn cc dt nn in prp$ nn . dt nn ,

lines.text: moreover, produces all the phenomena of this resistance without even
lines.pos: rb , vbz dt dt nns in dt nn in rb

lines.text: recognizing it as such; it is always a great advance to have brought him
lines.pos: vbg prp in jj ; prp vbz rb dt jj nn to vbp vbn prp

lines.text: to the point of understanding this conception and reckoning with it.
lines.pos: to dt nn in vbg dt nn cc vbg in prp .

lines.pos: in prp to vb in prp . prp vbz jj , rb , to vb in

lines.text: himself so many sacrifices of time, money, effort and self-denial in

lines.text: order to be freed. And yet he struggles, in the very interests of his
lines.pos: nn to vb vbn . cc rb prp vbz , in dt jj nns in prp$

lines.text: malady, against one who would help him. How improbable this assertion
lines.pos: nn , in cd wp md vb prp . wrb jj dt nn

lines.text: must sound! And yet it is so, and if we are reproached with its

lines.text: improbability, we need only answer that this fact is not without its

lines.text: analogies. Whoever goes to a dentist with an unbearable toothache may

lines.text: The resistance which the patient shows is highly varied, exceedingly

lines.text: constantly on his guard against the patient. In psychoanalytic therapy

lines.pos: nn cc nnp

lines.text: Probably you will term what I told you about ordinary nervousness in my

lines.pos: jj nn rbs jj cc jj nn . nnp vb

lines.text: their greatest source of suffering. It can attain a terrible intensity
lines.pos: prp$ jjs nn in vbg . prp md vb dt jj nn

lines.text: which may result in the wildest enterprises. But I do not wish to fall
lines.pos: wdt md nn in dt jjs nns . cc nnp vbp rb vbp to nn

lines.pos: jj in prp$ nns in dt nn . nnp vbp , in dt jj , to

lines.pos: to vb prp in prp in dt nn .

lines.text: Fear itself needs no introduction; everyone has at some time or other
lines.pos: nnp prp vbz dt nn ; nn vbz in dt nn cc jj

lines.text: known this sensation or, more precisely, this effect. It seems to me
lines.pos: vbn dt nn cc , jjr rb , dt nn . prp vbz to prp

lines.text: that we never seriously inquired why the nervous suffered so much more
lines.pos: in prp rb rb vbd wrb dt jj vbd rb jj jjr

lines.text: and so much more intensely under this condition. Perhaps it was thought
lines.pos: cc rb jj jjr rb in dt nn . rb prp vbd vbd

lines.pos: dt nn in nn ; prp vbz jj to vb dt nns " jj " cc

lines.text: "anxious" as though they meant the same thing. That is unjustifiable;
lines.pos: " jj " in in prp vbd dt jj nn . in vbz jj ;

lines.pos: ex vbp jj nns wp vbp rb jj , cc jj nns wp

lines.pos: vb in jj nns , cc rb in dt nn to nn .

lines.text: However that may be, it is certain that the problem of fear is the

lines.pos: vbg nn in jj jj nns , dt nn wp$ jj

lines.pos: nn md vb dt nn in nn in jj nn . nnp vbp rb nn

lines.text: that I can furnish you with this complete solution, but you will
lines.pos: in nnp md vb prp in dt jj nn , cc prp md

lines.text: certainly expect psychoanalysis to deal with this theme in a manner
lines.pos: rb vbp nns to jj in dt nn in dt nn

lines.text: different from that of the schools of medicine. These schools seem to be
lines.pos: jj in in in dt nns in nn . dt nns vb to vb

lines.text: interested primarily in the anatomical cause of the condition of fear.
lines.pos: jj rb in dt jj nn in dt nn in nn .

lines.text: They say the medulla oblongata is irritated, and the patient learns that
lines.pos: prp vbp dt nn nn vbz vbn , cc dt nn vbz in

lines.pos: prp vbz vbg in nn in dt nns jj . dt nn

lines.text: oblongata is a very serious and beautiful object. I remember exactly how
lines.pos: nn vbz dt jj jj cc jj nn . nnp vb rb wrb

lines.text: much time and trouble I devoted to the study of it, years ago. But today
lines.pos: jj nn cc nn nnp vbn to dt nn in prp , nns rb . cc nn

lines.text: I must say that I know of nothing more indifferent to me for the
lines.pos: nnp md vbp in nnp vb in nn jjr jj to prp in dt

lines.text: through which these sensations must pass.
lines.pos: in wdt dt nns md vb .

lines.text: One can talk about fear for a long time without even touching upon
lines.pos: cd md vb in nn in dt jj nn in rb vbg in

lines.text: nervousness. You will understand me without more ado, when I term this
lines.pos: nn . prp md vb prp in jjr nn , wrb nnp nn dt

lines.text: fear _real_ fear in contrast to _neurotic_ fear. Real fear seems quite
lines.pos: nn nn nn in nn to nn nn . jj nn vbz rb

lines.text: rational and comprehensible to us. We may testify that it is a reaction
lines.pos: jj cc nn to prp . prp md vb in prp vbz dt nn

lines.text: to the perception of external danger, viz., harm that is expected and
lines.pos: to dt nn in jj nn , nn . , nn in vbz vbn cc

lines.text: foreseen. It is related to the flight reflex and may be regarded as an

lines.text: expression of the instinct of self-preservation. And so the occasions,
lines.pos: nn in dt nn in nn . cc rb dt nns ,

lines.text: viz., the objects and situations which arouse fear, will depend largely

lines.text: woods, meaningless to the uninstructed, which reveals to him the
lines.pos: nns , jj to dt vbn , wdt vbz to prp dt

lines.pos: to dt nn prp vbz jj .

lines.text: After further consideration, we must say to ourselves that the verdict
lines.pos: in jj nn , prp md vbp to prp in dt nn

lines.pos: in jj nn , in prp vb jj cc jj , md vb rb

lines.text: happier ending: flight, defense, or possibly even attack. Under such a
lines.pos: jjr vbg : nn , nn , cc rb rb nn . in jj dt

lines.text: proceeding fear has absolutely no place; everything that happens would

lines.pos: vb vbn rb in rb cc jjr in dt nn in nn .

lines.text: You know that if fear is too strong, it proves absolutely useless and
lines.pos: prp vb in in nn vbz rb jj , prp vbz rb jj cc

lines.text: paralyzes every action, even flight. Generally the reaction against

lines.text: danger consists in a mixture of fear and resistance. The frightened

lines.pos: rb nn cc nn .

lines.text: We are therefore tempted to claim that the development of fear is never
lines.pos: prp vbp rb vbn to nn in dt nn in nn vbz rb

lines.text: purposeful. Perhaps closer examination will give us greater insight into
lines.pos: jj . rb jjr nn md vb prp jjr nn in

lines.text: the fear situation. The first factor is the expectancy of danger which
lines.pos: dt nn nn . dt nn nn vbz dt nn in nn wdt

lines.text: expresses itself in heightened sensory attention and in motor tension.
lines.pos: vbz prp in vbn jj nn cc in nn nn .

lines.text: This expectancy is undoubtedly advantageous; its absence may be
lines.pos: dt nn vbz rb jj ; prp$ nn md vb

lines.text: responsible for serious consequences. On the one hand, it gives rise to
lines.pos: jj in jj nns . in dt cd nn , prp vbz nn to

lines.text: motor activity, primarily to flight, and on a higher plane to active
lines.pos: nn nn , rb to nn , cc in dt jjr nn to jj

lines.text: the condition of fear. In so far as the development is still incipient,
lines.pos: dt nn in nn . in rb rb in dt nn vbz rb jj ,

lines.text: and is restricted to a mere signal, the more undisturbed the conversion
lines.pos: cc vbz vbn to dt jj jj , dt jjr jj dt nn

lines.text: of the readiness to be afraid into action the more purposeful the entire
lines.pos: in dt nn to vb jj in nn dt jjr jj dt jj

lines.text: proceeding. The readiness to be afraid seems to be the purposeful

lines.pos: nn .

lines.text: I avoid entering upon a discussion as to whether our language means the

lines.text: same or distinct things by the words anxiety, fear or fright. I think

lines.pos: in nn vbz vbn in nn in dt nn rb in dt

lines.text: on the other hand, seems really to possess a special meaning, which

lines.text: man from fright.

lines.text: You have probably noticed the ambiguity and vagueness in the use of the

lines.text: word "anxiety." Generally one means a subjective condition, caused by

lines.text: condition may be called an emotion. What is an emotion in the dynamic

lines.text: sense? Certainly something very complex. An emotion, in the first place,

lines.text: general sort, which belongs to the antecedent history of the species

lines.text: rather than to that of the individual. To be more clear: the emotional

lines.text: condition has a structure similar to that of an hysterical attack; it is

lines.pos: wdt vbz vb dt jj nn .

lines.text: Do not assume that what I have said here about emotions is derived from

lines.text: normal psychology. On the contrary, these are conceptions that have

lines.text: grown up with and are at home only in psychoanalysis. What psychology

lines.pos: vbz to vbp in nns cd dt nnp nn , in nn cd vbz

lines.text: absolutely incomprehensible for us psychoanalysts, and cannot be
lines.pos: rb jj in prp nns , cc md rb vb

lines.text: discussed. Of course, we do not consider our knowledge about emotions
lines.pos: vbn . in nn , prp vbp rb vb prp$ nn in nns

lines.pos: nn to nn , cc vbz rb in vbn in prp in dt nn in

lines.text: Let us extract the sum of our observations on the anxiety of children:
lines.pos: vb prp vb dt nn in prp$ nns in dt nn in nns :

lines.text: Infantile fear has very little to do with real fear, but is closely

lines.text: In phobias, for instance, two phases of the neurotic process can be
